Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PreferredNaming
Object: This subclassing is here to provide a pointer to clients as to which naming to use when otherwise not explicitly dictated by context

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/IncumbencyThatAffectsName
Object: A type of Incumbency that gives a IncumbencyPersonNaming, eg the office of Archbishop or Member of Parliament

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/TheUsage
Object: In a Peer's title, are they The Baron Of Placename or Baron Of Placename

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PostNominal
Object: A term or letters used after a person's name, eg. FRCOG

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/House
Object: A house in Parliament - i.e. the House of Lords or Commons

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/Member
Object: A member of a House of Parliament

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/Incumbency
Object: Acts as essentially a join between a person and a position, eg a job, something that a person has been appointed to

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/GenderIdentity
Object: Links a person to the gender identity they publically displayed

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/CulturalOrdering
Object: In using more meaningful semantic terms such as 'given name' rather than 'first name' we encounter cultural issues when the names are displayed in full - should the family name or given name be listed first?  This class is a proposed way of allowing clients to understand that the naming in question is eg. from a culture where the given name comes before the family name

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/hasPersonNaming
Object: Connects a person to their PersonNaming

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PeerageAuthority
Object: An authority that a peerage can be awarded in. e.g. an Scottish peerage or a UK peerage.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PeerageRank
Object: The peerage system is explicitly ranked, with a Baron being junior to an Earl.  This level number will allow clients to display the more senior peergae where a peer has more than one peerage per Lords convention

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PreNominal
Object: A term or letters used before a person's name, eg. General

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/OfUsage
Object: In a Peer's title, are they Baron Placename or Baron Of Placename

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PersonNaming
Object: Could also be called 'identity' if that wasn't so ambiguous.  ie People often have more than one naming over the course of their lives, from people changing their surnames at marriage to people being given appointments that have styles of address

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/preNominalOrdering
Object: States the position in which a PreNominal is listed

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PeerageNaming
Object: a type of PersonNaming that has been influenced by someone's peerage, whether that be through birth or through appointment to the House Of Lords

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/PeerageType
Object: Type of peerage, eg Life or Hereditary

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/postNominalOrdering
Object: States the position in which a PostNominal is listed

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/NamingQualification
Object: A qualification or professional achievement which grants someone a pre-nominal or post-nominal decoration to their name, eg. attaining a doctorate allowing you to use the pre-nominal Dr or the post-nominal PhD

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/HouseSeat
Object: A seat in a House in Parliament

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/SeatIncumbency
Object: The time someone is in a HouseSeat

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/IncumbencyPersonNaming
Object: This is a PersonNaming that comes directly from a person's Incumbency - eg The Archbishop Of Canterbury, or an MP taking the initials MP

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/Peerage
Object: This refers to the actual fact that a Person is awarded a Peerage.  This should probably be modelled differently but is here a placeholder as of 8-6-17

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/person-name/
Object: Person name ontology for UK Parliament.
